{{about|the [[James Patterson]] book about Cory Friedman|the article about the medical term "against medical advice"|Against medical advice}} {{Infobox book | name = Against Medical Advice: A True Story | title_orig = | translator = | image = James Patterson - Against Medical Advice One Family's Struggle with an Agonizing Medical Mystery.jpeg | caption = | author = [[James Patterson]], Hal Friedman | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = United States | language = English | series = | genre = [[Non-fiction]] | publisher = [[Little, Brown and Company]] | release_date = October 20, 2008 | english_release_date = | media_type = Print ([[Hardcover|Hardback]] & [[e-book]]) | pages = 368 pp (first edition, hardback) | isbn = 978-0-316-02504-1 | isbn_note = (first edition, hardback) | dewey= | congress= | oclc= | preceded_by = | followed_by = }}
'''''Against Medical Advice: A True Story''''' is a [[The New York Times Non-Fiction Best Sellers of 2008|New York Times Bestselling]] non-fiction book by [[James Patterson]] and Hal Friedman,<ref>{{cite web|last=Sheehan|first=Nancy|title=Tourette agony|url=http://www.telegram.com/article/20090919/NEWS/909190333/0/NEWS07|publisher=News Telegram|accessdate=20 November 2012}}</ref> detailing the illness and medical struggles of Cory Friedman and his family.<ref>{{cite news|title=Best-sellers|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=RM&p_theme=rm&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=12450DBE1CCC2970&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|accessdate=19 November 2012|newspaper=Rocky Mountain News|date=November 7, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Hardcover Nonfiction Published: October 31, 2008|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/11/09/books/bestseller/besthardnonfiction.html|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130130133034/http://www.nytimes.com/2008/11/09/books/bestseller/besthardnonfiction.html|dead-url=yes|archive-date=30 January 2013|publisher=New York Times|accessdate=20 November 2012|date=9 November 2008}} </ref> The book was published on October 20, 2008, by [[Little, Brown and Company]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Brophy Marcus|first=Mary|title='Against Medical Advice' chronicles Tourette's struggle|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/news/health/2008-10-19-against-medical-advice-tourettes-patterson_N.htm|publisher=USA Today|accessdate=20 November 2012|date=20 October 2008}}</ref>
==Synopsis== ''Against Medical Advice'' begins with a seventeen-year-old Cory arriving at the Dressler Psychiatric Hospital for alcohol abuse, with him detailing the various medications he is on and how he feels that they do nothing for him. Cory expresses frustration over giving the appearance of being insane, despite his not feeling as if he was. The book shows how Cory began exhibiting uncontrollable urges to perform body tics and say various things at the age of five years. As he grew up, he was put through several different treatments, which contributed to his feelings of helplessness. Since he is unable to control his actions due to having [[OCD]], [[Tourette syndrome]], and an anxiety disorder, Cory experienced ridicule in his life and had troubles living the everyday life of a child, which is exacerbated by ill medical treatment.<ref>{{cite news|last=CONNELLY|first=SHERRYL|title=More book reviews: Sister Souljah's fiction, James Patterson's truth|url=http://articles.nydailynews.com/2008-11-09/entertainment/17911050_1_sister-souljah-cory-james-patterson|accessdate=20 November 2012|newspaper=New York Daily News|date=November 9, 2008}}</ref>
==Med Head== In 2010, Cory Friedman published a young adult version of ''Against Medical Advice'' with Patterson, entitled ''Med Head: My Knock-Down Drag-Out Drugged-Up Battle with My Brain''.<ref>{{cite web|title=AUTHOR TALK: Cory Friedman |url=http://www.teenreads.com.asp1-14.dfw1-2.websitetestlink.com/authors/au-friedman-cory.asp |publisher=Teen Reads |accessdate=20 November 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130203022433/http://www.teenreads.com.asp1-14.dfw1-2.websitetestlink.com/authors/au-friedman-cory.asp |archivedate=3 February 2013 |df= }}</ref> The book was released on April 1, 2010, and received a positive review from TeenReads and [[Kirkus Reviews]], who called it a "perfect prescription for misery-memoir maniacs".<ref>{{cite web|title=Med Head: My Knock-Down Drag-Out Drugged-Up Battle with My Brain|url=http://www.teenreads.com/reviews/med-head-my-knock-down-drag-out-drugged-up-battle-with-my-brain|publisher=Teen Reads|accessdate=20 November 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Review: Med Head|url=http://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/james-patterson/med-head/|publisher=Kirkus Reviews|accessdate=20 November 2012}}</ref>
==Reception== [[Diário Digital]] gave a positive review for ''Against Medical Advice'', calling it "a touching story of courage, determination and the ultimate triumph of a family facing a desperate situation".<ref>{{cite web|title=Quinta Essência edita "Força de Vontade"|url=https://diariodigital.sapo.pt/news.asp?id_news=440551|publisher=Diário Digital|accessdate=20 November 2012}}</ref> The [[Carlsbad Current-Argus]] also praised the book, stating that it was a "success".<ref>{{cite news|title=Patterson's foray into nonfiction a success|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=NewsLibrary&p_multi=CCAB&d_place=CCAB&p_theme=newslibrary2&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=12689E7D9B7367A0&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|accessdate=20 November 2012|newspaper=Carlsbad Current-Argus|date=February 21, 2009}}</ref>
