The '''maxillary lateral incisors''' are a pair of upper ([[maxilla]]ry) [[tooth|teeth]] that are located laterally (away from the midline of the [[face]]) from both [[maxillary central incisor]]s of the [[mouth]] and medially (toward the midline of the face) from both [[maxillary canine]]s.  As with all [[incisor]]s, their function is for [[Shearing (physics)|shearing]] or cutting food during [[mastication]], commonly known as chewing.  There are generally no [[cusp (dentistry)|cusp]]s on the teeth, but the rare condition known as [[talon cusp]]s are most prevalent on the maxillary lateral incisors.<ref>{{Cite book |url=http://www.hindawi.com/archive/2014/595189/ |title=Journal of Oral Diseases |last=Sharma |first=Gaurav |last2=Nagpal |first2=Archna |date=2014 |volume=2014 |pages=1–6 |language=en |doi=10.1155/2014/595189 |issn=2356-7538}}</ref> The surface area of the tooth used in eating is called an incisal ridge or incisal edge.  Though relatively the same, there are some minor differences between the [[deciduous teeth|deciduous]] (baby) maxillary lateral incisor and that of the [[permanent teeth|permanent]] maxillary lateral incisor. The maxillary lateral incisors [[occlusion (dentistry)|occlude]] in opposition to the [[mandibular lateral incisor]]s.

==Notation==

In the [[Universal numbering system (dental)|universal system of notation]], the deciduous maxillary lateral incisors are designated by a letter written in uppercase.{{sfn|Nelson|2015|p=5}} The right deciduous maxillary lateral incisor is known as "D", and the left one is known as "G".{{sfn|Nelson|2015|p=5}} The [[FDI World Dental Federation notation|international notation]] has a different system of notation.  Thus, the right deciduous maxillary lateral incisor known as "52", and the left one is known as "62".{{sfn|Nelson|2015|p=4}}
[[File:Maxillary lateral incisors01-01-06.png|right|thumb|220px|Maxillary lateral incisors of permanent and primary teeth are marked in red.]]
In the universal system of notation, the permanent maxillary lateral incisors are designated by a number.{{sfn|Nelson|2015|p=5}} The right permanent maxillary lateral incisor is known as "7", and the left one is known as "10".{{sfn|Nelson|2015|p=5}}{{sfn|Levin-Goldstein|Short|2013}} In the [[Palmer notation]], a number is used in conjunction with a symbol designating in which quadrant the tooth is found.{{sfn|Nelson|2015|p=5}} For this tooth, the left and right lateral incisors would have the same number, "2", but the right one would have the symbol, "┘", underneath it, while the left one would have, "└".{{sfn|Nelson|2015|p=5}} The [[FDI World Dental Federation notation|FDI notation]] has a different numbering system than the previous two, and the right permanent maxillary lateral incisor is known as "12", and the left one is known as "22".{{sfn|Nelson|2015|p=5}}

==Development==

The primary tooth will begin to show signs of development between 14 {{frac|2|3}} weeks and 16 {{frac|1|2}} weeks in utero, at an average of 16 weeks.{{sfn|Nelson|2015|p=36}}

The permanent tooth typically will erupt between when the child is 8 or 9 years old, while the root will continue to mineralize until around 11 years old.{{sfn|Levin-Goldstein|Short|2013}}. The tooth's crown will conclude its development around the age of 4 or 5.{{sfn|Levin-Goldstein|Short|2013}}

==Deciduous dentition==

There are two maxillary lateral incisors in the deciduous dentition.{{sfn|Nelson|2015|p=43}} The teeth have a more curved distoincisal angle than the primary maxillary central incisor.{{sfn|Nelson|2015|p=51}} The tooth is longer cervicoincisally than it is mesiodistally.{{sfn|Nelson|2015|p=51}} The average length of the primary lateral incisor is 15.8 mm, with the average crown length being 5.6 mm and the root length average being 11.4 mm.{{sfn|Nelson|2015|p=50}}

All primary teeth have several characteristics that are different when compared to the permanent dentition.{{sfn|Nelson|2015|p=44-5}} The primary lateral incisor crown is wider mesiodistally than the permanent tooth and the roots of the primary lateral incisors are longer than the permanent tooth.{{sfn|Nelson|2015|p=44-5}} The cervical ridges in all of anterior teeth are more prominent than in the 

==Permanent dentition==

There are two maxillary lateral incisors in the permanent dentition,{{sfn|Nelson|2015|p=43}} which begin to show signs of development at 10 to 12 months after birth.{{sfn|Nelson|2015|p=36}} The maxillary lateral incisor resembles the [[maxillary central incisor]], but is smaller in every dimension aside from root length.{{sfn|Nelson|2015|p=104}} The root of the lateral incisor is around 1.5 times the length of the crown.{{sfn|Nelson|2015|p=106}} The tooth has the most variability in crown shape in the mouth except the [[maxillary third molar]].{{sfn|Nelson|2015|p=104}} The two lateral incisors can also be congenitally missing.{{sfn|Nelson|2015|p=105}} The teeth are less pigmented and are whiter in appearance than the permanent teeth.{{sfn|Nelson|2015|p=44-5}}

===Labial aspect===

Compared to the maxillary central incisor, the maxillary lateral incisor has more rounded mesial and distal incisal angles.{{sfn|Nelson|2015|p=106}} The distal outline is always more rounded.{{sfn|Nelson|2015|p=106}} The root is often tapered distally, often with a sharp curve distally and to an apex; however, the curve can be absent.{{sfn|Nelson|2015|p=106}} The mesial and distal contacts are more cervical than the central incisor.{{sfn|Levin-Goldstein|Short|2013}} The surface is smooth.{{sfn|Nelson|2015|p=107}} The labial view of the lateral incisor fits into the geometric shape of a trapezoid.{{sfn|Nelson|2015|p=72-3}}

===Lingual aspect===

The distal and mesial marginal ridges are evident and the cingulum is prominent.{{sfn|Nelson|2015|p=107}} The lingual fossa is more concave than the central incisor.{{sfn|Nelson|2015|p=107}} The cingulum will often have a deep developmental groove on the distal side that can continue well into the root.{{sfn|Nelson|2015|p=107}} The lingual view of the lateral incisor fits into the geometric shape of a trapezoid.{{sfn|Nelson|2015|p=72-3}}

===Mesial aspect===

The curvature of the [[cementoenamel junction]] (CEJ) sharply inclines towards the incisal ridge.{{sfn|Nelson|2015|p=107-9}} The mesial view of the lateral incisor fits into the geometric shape of a triangle.{{sfn|Nelson|2015|p=72-3}}

===Distal aspect===

Compared to the tooth's mesial view of the cervical line, the distal cervical line is slightly more cervical by close to a millimeter.{{sfn|Nelson|2015|p=107-9}} There may be a developmental groove present for all or most of the length.{{sfn|Nelson|2015|p=109}} The distal view of the lateral incisor fits into the geometric shape of a triangle.{{sfn|Nelson|2015|p=72-3}}

