'''Washington Apple Health''' is the [[Medicaid]] and [[State Children's Health Insurance Program]]s offered in Washington state. The program was initiated January 1, 2014.<ref>{{citation|author=John Webster|title=STATE TRIES TO SIMPLIFY MEDICAID Apple Health Program Aims to Reduce Sign-Up time,ER Trips|newspaper=[[The Spokesman-Review]]|location=Spokane, WA|date=July 23, 2013|via=[[HighBeam]] {{subscription required}}|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-34938465.html}}</ref> It was preceded in 2008 by a [[children's health]] plan run by the [[Washington State Department of Social and Health Services]] called "Apple Health for Kids".<ref>{{citation|title=DEPARTMENT OF SOCIAL AND HEALTH SERVICES LAUNCHES NEW APPLE HEALTH FOR KIDS - NEW INITIATIVE TO BOOST ENROLLMENT IN CHILDREN'S MEDICAL COVERAGE|publisher=Washington State Department of Social and Health Services|type=press release|date=March 10, 2009|via=[[HighBeam]] {{subscription required}}|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P3-1522965421.html}}</ref> In 2016, the plan was ordered by a Federal district court judge to include a coverage treatment with a certain drug for [[Hepatitis C]] to all  28,000 patients with the disease, not only those who qualified based on degree of liver damage.<ref>{{citation|title=Judge orders Washington Medicaid to provide lifesaving hepatitis C drugs for all
|author=JoNel Aleccia |date=May 28, 2016|newspaper=[[The Seattle Times]]|url=http://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/health/judge-orders-apple-health-to-cover-hepatitis-c-drugs-for-all/}}</ref> 

